<chapter xml:id="transformations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Linear Transformations</title>

<!-- Objectives -->
    <objectives>
            <ul>
                <li> Understand linear transformations both algebraically and graphically.</li>
                <li> Be able to perform basic matrix operations.</li>
                <li> Be able to connect ideas about one-to-one and onto transformations with systems of equations.</li>
                <li> Be able to connect ideas about kernels and images with null spaces and column spaces.</li>
                <li> Be able to calculate orthogonal projections onto a subspace.</li>
                <li> See how to use a computer algebra system to help perform basic operations and apply linear algebra to data analysis in a basic way.</li>
            </ul>
    </objectives>


<!-- Introduction -->

    <introduction>
        <p>
            In this unit we will explore how we can transform one vector spaces into another.
        </p>
    </introduction>

<!-- Intro to Linear TRansformations -->

    <section xml:id="section_morphisams">
        <title>Isomorphisms and Homomorphisms of Vector Spaces</title>
        <idx><h>isomorphism</h></idx><idx><h>homomorphism</h></idx>
        <subsection>
            <title>Homorphisms and Functions</title>
            <definition>
                <statement>
                    <p><idx><h>function</h></idx><idx><h>homomorphism</h></idx><idx><h>linear map</h></idx>
                        A <term>function</term> is a relation, call it <m>A</m>, from one set called the <em>domain</em>, <m>X</m>, to another set called the <em>codomain</em>, <m>Y</m> such that
                        <ul>
                            <li><m>\forall x\in X,\ \exists y\in Y:\ A(x)=y</m></li>, and
                            <li><m>\forall x\in X:</m> if <m>y_1=A(x)</m> and <m>y_2=A(x)</m>, then <m>y_1=y_2</m>.</li>
                        </ul>
                        If in addition we know that <m>A(ax+by)=a\, A(x)\, +\, b\, A(y)</m> we say that the function is a <term>homomorphism</term>, or that it is a <term>linear map</term>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>
            <investigation xml:id="basic_linear_exmaple">
                <title>Something Linear</title>
                <p>
                    Let <m>f:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}</m> be defined by <m>f(x)=-7x</m> and let's see that this is linear.  First, since both the input and output for the function comes from <m>\mathbb{R}</m> that is the domain and the codomain.  If <m>x=ax_1+bx_2</m>, then we get
                    <md>
                        <mrow>f(x)\amp = f\left(ax_1+bx_2\right)\amp\amp \mbox{definition of}\ x</mrow>
                        <mrow>    \amp = -7\left(ax_1+bx_2\right)\amp\amp \mbox{definition of}\ f</mrow>
                        <mrow>    \amp = -7ax_1-7bx_2 \amp\amp \mbox{distributive property}</mrow>
                        <mrow>    \amp = a\left(-7x_1\right)+b\left(-7x_2\right) \amp\amp \mbox{commutative property}</mrow>
                        <mrow>    \amp = af\left(x_1\right)+bf\left(x_2\right)\amp\amp \mbox{definition of}\ f</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Therefore, <m>f(x)</m> satisfies the definition of a homomorphism (linear function).
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation xml:id="derivative_of_cubic">
                <title>Also Linear</title>
                <p>
                    Let <m>d:\mathcal{P}_3\rightarrow\mathcal{P}_3</m> be defined by <m>d(f)=3ax^2+2bx+c</m> and let's see that this too is linear.  First, since both the input and output for the function comes from <m>\mathcal{P}_3</m> that is the domain and the codomain.  If <m>f(x)=a_1x^3+b_1x^2+c_1x+d_1</m> and <m>g(x)=a_2x^3+b_2x^2+c_2x+d_2</m>, then we get
                    <me>(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)=(a_1+a_2)x^3+(b_1+b_2)x^2+(c_1+c_2)x+(d_1+d_2)</me>
                    and when we apply the function <m>d</m>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>d(f+g)\amp = 3(a_1+a_2)x^2+2(b_1+b_2)x+(c_1+c_2) \amp\amp \mbox{definition of}\ d</mrow>
                        <mrow>    \amp = 3a_1x^2+3a_2x^2+2b_1x+2b_2x+c_1+c_2\amp\amp \mbox{distributive property}</mrow>
                        <mrow>    \amp = (3a_1x^2+2b_1x+c_1)+(3a_2x^2+2b_2x+c_2) \amp\amp \mbox{commutative property}</mrow>
                        <mrow>    \amp = d(f)+d(g) \amp\amp \mbox{definition of}\ d</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Therefore, <m>d</m> satisfies the definition of a homomorphism (linear function).
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation xml:id="vector_map_eg1">
                <title>Something with Vectors</title>
                <p>
                    Define <m>T:\mathbb{R}^3\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^2</m> by
                    <me>
                        T\left(
                            \begin{array}{c}
                                x \\ y \\ z
                            \end{array}
                        \right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{c}
                                x+z \\ y+z
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    For example:
                    <me>
                        T\left(
                            \begin{array}{c}
                                1 \\ 0 \\ 1
                            \end{array}
                        \right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                2 \\ 1
                            \end{array}
                        \right)\mbox{ or }
                        T\left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                3 \\ 1 \\ 5
                            \end{array}
                        \right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                8 \\ 6
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    This is a linear map since
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            T\left(
                                \begin{array}{c}
                                    x_1+x_2 \\ y_1+y_2 \\ z_1+z_2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)\amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{c}
                                    x_1+x_2+z_1+z_2 \\ y_1+y_2+z_1+z_2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =\left(
                                \begin{array}{c}
                                    x_1+z_1 \\ y_1+z_1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)+
                             \left(
                                \begin{array}{c}
                                    x_2+z_2 \\ y_2+z_2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp=
                            T\left(
                                \begin{array}{c}
                                    x_1 \\ y_1 \\ z_1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)+
                            T\left(
                                \begin{array}{c}
                                    x_2 \\ y_2 \\ z_2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <sidebyside>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Basis for <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m></caption>
                        <image width="60%" source="images/r3_basis.png" />
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Transformation of the basis for <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> by <m>T</m></caption>
                        <image width="20%" source="images/r2_basis_with_diagonal.png" />
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
            </investigation>
            <investigation xml:id="line_not_linear">
                <title>Surprisingly Not Linear</title>
                <p>
                    Let <m>f:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}</m> be defined by <m>f(x)=x+1</m> and let's see that this is not linear.  Since we want to see that something is not the case we just need a counter example.  If <m>x=1</m> and <m>y=2</m> then
                    <me>f(x)+f(y)=f(1)+f(2)=2+3=5,</me>
                    but
                    <me>f(x+y)=f(3)=4</me>
                    so that <m>f(x)+f(y)\neq f(x+y)</m>, i.e. <m>f</m> is not linear.  This may be surprising since <m>f(x)=x+1</m> is a line, but this is what is called an <term>affine map</term> since it is the sum of a linear map and a constant.<idx><h>affine map</h></idx>
                </p>
            </investigation>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Isomorphisms (one-to-one and onto)</title>
            <definition xml:id="one_to_one_onto">
                <statement><idx><h>one-to-one</h></idx><idx><h>1-1</h></idx><idx><h>onto</h></idx><idx><h>isomorphism</h></idx>
                    <p>
                        A function <m>f:V\rightarrow W</m> is <term>one-to-one</term> if for all <m>v_1,v_2\in V</m>, <m>f(v_1)=f(v_2)</m> implies <m>v_1=v_2</m>.  The function is <term>onto</term> if for all <m>w\in W</m> there exists <m>v\in V</m> such that <m>f(v)=w</m>. A function which is both is called an <term>isomorphism</term>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>
            <p>
                Looking back at <xref ref="basic_linear_exmaple"/> the function is an isomorphism. If <m>-7x_1=-7x_2</m>, then <m>x_1=x_2</m> and <m>f</m> is one-to-one.  Also, for any <m>y</m>, <me>y=-7\left(-\frac{1}{7}y\right)</me> so that when <m>x=-\frac{1}{7}y</m> we get <m>f(x)=y</m> and <m>f</m> is onto.
            </p>
            <p>
                In <xref ref="derivative_of_cubic"/>, <me>d(x^3+7)=d(x^3-9)</me> so that <m>d</m> is not 1-1. Also, for all cubics the output of <m>d</m> is a quadratic so it is not onto, nothing gives the output <m>x^3</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Finally, in <xref ref="vector_map_eg1"/> the map is onto but not 1-1.  We could set up systems of equations and show this (and you should try that on your own), but it is better to try and understand this intuitively.  The map <m>T</m> maps three dimensions onto two.  Since the output of the map, the <term>image</term><idx><h>image</h></idx>, has more than two different vectors it is onto.  But, since we are squeezing three dimensions down to two it can't be 1-1.<fn>This is a very imprecise way of looking at it but it is good a good visual.</fn>
            </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Kernel, Domain, and Image</title>
            <definition xml:id="kernel"><idx><h>kernel</h></idx>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The <term>Kernel</term> of a transformation <m>T:V\rightarrow W</m> is the set of all <m>\vec{v}\in V</m> such that <m>T(\vec{v})=\vec{0}</m>.  A transformation is one-to-one if and only if the kernel contains only the zero vector.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>
            <p>
                Above in <xref ref="vector_map_eg1"/> any vector of the form <m>\vec{v}=\left\lt-z,-z,z\right\gt</m> maps to <m>\left\lt 0,0\right\gt</m>:
                <me>
                    T\left(
                        \begin{array}{c}
                            -z \\ -z \\ z
                        \end{array}
                    \right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{c}
                            -z+z \\ -z+z
                        \end{array}
                    \right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{c}
                            0 \\ 0
                        \end{array}
                    \right).
                </me>
                And so we could show that the kernel of <m>T</m> is <m>span\left\{\left\lt-1,-1,1\right\gt\right\}</m>.  Significantly, we can use this to rewrite every element of the domain as
                <me>
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            x\\ y \\z
                        \end{array}
                    \right) = 
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            x+z\\ y+z \\0
                        \end{array}
                    \right) + 
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            -z\\ -z \\z
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                </me>
                so that it is the sum of something in the kernel and something that is not in the kernel unless it happens that <m>x=y=-z</m>.  This is a small example of a much more general truth, and we will use this later when we discuss orthogonal projections and curve fitting.
            </p>
            <p>
                As a final note you can see that the non-kernel piece of the above vector looks just like the image (or output) of the transformation:
                <me>
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            x+z\\ y+z \\0
                        \end{array}
                    \right)\ \mbox{ versus }
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            x+z\\ y+z
                        \end{array}
                    \right).
                </me>
                This too is a part of the a larger picture and it tells us that in a sense the non-kernel portion of the domain is isomorphic to the image of the transformation.
            </p>
        </subsection>

    </section>

<!-- Matrix operations and Maps -->

    <section xml:id="section_matrix_operations">
        <title>Matrix Operations</title>
        <subsection>
            <title>Basic Matrix Arithmetic</title>
            <investigation>
                <title>
                    Addition
                </title>
                <p>
                     Matrix addition is done term by term.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    2\amp 0 \amp 5\\
                                    -1\amp 3 \amp 4
                                \end{array}
                            \right)+
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    0\amp 5 \amp 1\\
                                    1\amp 7 \amp -2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)\amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    2+0\amp 0+5 \amp 5+1\\
                                    -1+1\amp 3+7 \amp 4+(-2)
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    2\amp 5 \amp 6\\
                                    0\amp 10 \amp 2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title>Scalar Multiplication</title>
                <p>
                    Scalar multiplication is likewise done term by term.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>5
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    2\amp 0 \amp 5\\
                                    -1\amp 3 \amp 4
                                \end{array}
                            \right)\amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    5(2)\amp 5(0) \amp 5(5)\\
                                    5(-1)\amp 5(3) \amp 5(4)
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    10\amp 0 \amp 25\\
                                    -5\amp 15 \amp 20
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title>Matrix Multiplication</title>
                <p>
                    Multiply the rows of the first matrix by the columns of the second, multiplication is taking the dot product of rows with columns.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    2\amp 0 \amp 5\\
                                    -1\amp 3 \amp 4
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    0\amp 5 \\
                                    1\amp 7 \\
                                    0\amp 1 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)\amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    2(0)+0(1)+5(0) \amp 2(5)+0(7)+5(1) \\
                                    -1(0)+3(1)+4(0) \amp -1(5)+3(7)+4(1)
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    0\amp 15 \\
                                    3\amp 20
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title>Putting it All Together:</title>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1\amp -7 \\
                                    3\amp 2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)+
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr}
                                    2\amp 0 \amp 5\\
                                    -1\amp 3 \amp 4
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    0\amp 5 \\
                                    1\amp 7 \\
                                    0\amp 1 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)\amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    2(1)\amp 2(-7) \\
                                    2(3)\amp 2(2)
                                \end{array}
                            \right)+
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    2(0)+0(1)+5(0) \amp 2(5)+0(7)+5(1) \\
                                    -1(0)+3(1)+4(0) \amp -1(5)+3(7)+4(1)
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    2\amp -14 \\
                                    6\amp 4
                                \end{array}
                            \right)+
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    0 \amp 15 \\
                                    3 \amp 20
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    2+0 \amp -14+15 \\
                                    6+3 \amp 4+20
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    2 \amp 1 \\
                                    9 \amp 24
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </investigation>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Invertible Matrices</title>
            <definition><idx><h>inverse matrix</h></idx><idx><h>left inverse</h></idx><idx><h>right inverse</h></idx>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A matrix <m>A</m> is <term>invertible</term> is there exists a matrix <m>A^{-1}</m> such that <m>A\, A^{-1}=A^{-1}\, A=I</m> where <m>I</m> is the identity matrix.  If there exists <m>B</m> such that only <m>A\, B=I</m> and <m>B\, A\neq I</m>, then <m>B</m> is the <term>right inverse</term> of <m>A</m> and <m>A</m> is the <term>left inverse</term> of <m>B</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>
            <investigation>
                <title><m>2\times 2</m> - Matrix Version 1</title>
                <p>
                    Find the inverse of
                    <me>
                        A=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                2 \amp 5 \\
                                3 \amp 8
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    We want to find
                    <me>
                        A^{-1}=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                a \amp b \\
                                c \amp d
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    so that
                    <me>
                        A\, A^{-1}=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                2 \amp 5 \\
                                3 \amp 8
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                a \amp b \\
                                c \amp d
                            \end{array}
                        \right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                1 \amp 0 \\
                                0 \amp 1
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    Multiplyting as above this reduces to
                    <me>
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                2a+5c \amp 2b+5d \\
                                3a+8c \amp 3b+8d
                            \end{array}
                        \right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                1 \amp 0 \\
                                0 \amp 1
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    or
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2a+5c=1</mrow>
                        <mrow>3a+8c=0</mrow>
                    </md>
                    and
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2b+5d=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>3b+8d=1.</mrow>
                    </md>
                    We get two sets of two equations each with two variables.  Writing each of these as augmented matrices we get
                    <me>
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr|r}
                                2 \amp 5 \amp 1\\
                                3 \amp 8 \amp 0
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    and
                    <me>
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr|r}
                                2 \amp 5 \amp 0\\
                                3 \amp 8 \amp 1
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    Solving each of these we would get <m>a=8</m>, <m>b=-5</m>, <m>c=-3</m>, and <m>d=2</m>, so
                    <me>
                        A^{-1}=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                8 \amp -5 \\
                                -3 \amp 2
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    But, notice that the coefficient matrices are the same for both systems of equations, they are both <m>A</m>, so that when we reduce them we follow the same steps each time, this gives us a better way to approach this.
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title><m>2\times 2</m> - Matrix Version 2</title>
                <p>
                    Find the inverse of
                    <me>
                        A=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                2 \amp 5 \\
                                3 \amp 8
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    We want to find
                    <me>
                        A^{-1}=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                a \amp b \\
                                c \amp d
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    so that
                    <me>
                        A\, A^{-1}=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                2 \amp 5 \\
                                3 \amp 8
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                a \amp b \\
                                c \amp d
                            \end{array}
                        \right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                1 \amp 0 \\
                                0 \amp 1
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    From above we want a coefficient matrix that matches <m>A</m> and then two vectors on the right which together match the identity matrix, so it looks like this
                    <me>
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                2 \amp 5 \amp 1\amp 0\\
                                3 \amp 8 \amp 0 \amp 1
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    Let's see what we get when we row reduce the left hand side:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                    2 \amp 5 \amp 1\amp 0\\
                                    3 \amp 8 \amp 0 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)\amp \leadsto 
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                    3 \amp 8 \amp 0\amp 1\\
                                    2 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 0
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp \leadsto 
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                    3 \amp 8 \amp 0\amp 1\\
                                    2 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 0
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp \leadsto 
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                    1 \amp 3 \amp -1\amp 1\\
                                    2 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 0
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp \leadsto 
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                    1 \amp 3 \amp -1\amp 1\\
                                    0 \amp -1 \amp 3 \amp -2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp \leadsto 
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                    1 \amp 3 \amp -1\amp 1\\
                                    0 \amp 1 \amp -3 \amp 2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp \leadsto 
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp 8\amp -5\\
                                    0 \amp 1 \amp -3 \amp 2
                                \end{array}
                            \right).
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    What we got on the right is exactly the inverse we wanted
                    <me>
                        A^{-1}=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                8 \amp -5 \\
                                -3 \amp 2
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    This is really the same thing we did before, but we did it all at once to save time.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="two_by_two_inverse">
                    As a final note on <m>2\times 2</m> matrices if
                    <me>
                        A=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                a \amp b \\
                                c \amp d
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    then it turns out
                    <me>
                        A^{-1}=\frac{1}{ad-bc}\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                d \amp -b \\
                                -c \amp a
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    provided <m>ad-bc\neq 0</m>; if <m>ad-bc=0</m> then <m>A</m> doesn't have an inverse.  Unfortunately, there is not such a simple formula for larger matrices.
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title>Inverse of a <m>3\times 3</m> Matrix </title>
                <p>
                    Find the inverse of
                    <me>
                        A=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rrr}
                                1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
                                3 \amp 8 \amp 0 \\
                                0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \\
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    As before we set up an augmented matrix with <m>A</m> as the coefficients on the left and vectors on the right that when taken together look like the identity matrix, then we row reduce.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr|rrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                                    3 \amp 8 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                                    0 \amp 4 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \amp\leadsto
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr|rrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                                    0 \amp 8 \amp 3 \amp -3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                                    0 \amp 8 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp\leadsto
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr|rrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
                                    0 \amp 8 \amp 3 \amp -3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
                                    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp\leadsto
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr|rrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
                                    0 \amp 8 \amp 0 \amp -12 \amp 4 \amp -6 \\
                                    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp\leadsto
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrr|rrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
                                    0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -\frac{3}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{3}{4} \\
                                    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    So that we get
                    <me>
                        A^{-1}=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rrr}
                                 4 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\
                                 -\frac{3}{2} \amp \frac{1}{2} \amp -\frac{3}{4} \\
                                 3 \amp -1 \amp 2\\
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title>Inverse of a <m>4\times 4</m> Matrix </title>
                <p>
                    Find the inverse of
                    <me>
                        A=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rrrr}
                                1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 5 \\
                                3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 15\\
                                0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0\\
                                7 \amp 5 \amp 8 \amp 36
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    As before we set up an augmented matrix with <m>A</m> as the coefficients on the left and vectors on the right that when taken together look like the identity matrix, then we row reduce.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrrr|rrrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 5 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
                                    3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 15 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                    2 \amp 3 \amp -7 \amp 11 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \amp\leadsto
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrrr|rrrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 5  \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 1 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp -3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 3 \amp -9 \amp 1  \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp\leadsto
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrrr|rrrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 5  \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 1 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp -3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1  \amp 7 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp\leadsto
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrrr|rrrr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0  \amp -37 \amp 16 \amp -1 \amp -5\\
                                    0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 6 \amp -2 \amp 3 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                    0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1  \amp 7 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    So that we get
                    <me>
                        A^{-1}=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rrrr}
                                    -37 \amp 16 \amp -1 \amp -5\\
                                    6 \amp -2 \amp 3 \amp 0\\
                                    3 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                    7 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right).
                    </me>
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title>A Couple Non-Examples</title>
                <p>
                    Suppose that we were given
                    <me>
                        A=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                2 \amp 3 \\
                                4 \amp 6\\
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    and we were asked to find the inverse, could we do it? From what we mentioned above (<xref ref="two_by_two_inverse" />) we know the answer is no because <m>2(6)-3(4)=0</m>.  But, what woudl happen if we ignored this and tried any ways:
                    <me>
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                4 \amp 6 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                        \leadsto
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr|rr}
                                2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                0 \amp 0 \amp -2 \amp 1\\
                            \end{array}
                        \right),
                    </me>
                    which is an inconsistent system.  This happens because the row space of <m>A</m> is one dimensional, it is a single line in the direction of <m>\left(2,3\right)</m>, but it exists in two dimensions.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="one_d_row_space">
                    <caption>One Dimensional Row Space for a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix</caption>
                    <image width="50%" source="images/row_space_oneD.png"/>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    Now for a larger example, if we try to get an inverse for
                    <me>
                        A=\left(
                            \begin{array}{rrr}
                                1 \amp 0 \amp -1\\
                                0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    we get
                    <me>
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rrr|rrr}
                                1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
                                0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                        \leadsto
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rrr|rrr}
                                1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
                                0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                                0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 1\\
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    We can't row reduce <m>A</m> so we don't get an inverse.  This is happening because the rows of <m>A</m> are not linearly independent, the row space for <m>A</m> is
                    <md>
                        <mrow>Row\ A\amp=\left\{\left( 1,0,-1\right), \left( 0,1,0\right) \right\}</mrow>
                    </md>
                    which is only two dimensional.  That is, a matrix which in a sense has a two dimensional span but exists in three dimensions doesn't have an inverse.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="two_d_row_space">
                    <caption>Two Dimensional Row Space for a <m>3\times 3</m> matrix</caption>
                    <image width="70%" source="images/row_space_twoD.png"/>
                </figure>
                <p>
                    Note that while <m>A</m> doesn't have an inverse
                    <me>
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rrr}
                                1 \amp 0 \amp -1\\
                                0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                1 \amp 0 \\
                                0 \amp 1 \\
                                0 \amp 0 \\
                            \end{array}
                        \right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                1 \amp 0 \\
                                0 \amp 1 \\
                            \end{array}
                        \right),
                    </me>
                </p>
                so that a matrix with the same row space has a <em>right inverse</em>.<fn>You should convince yourself that it doesn't have a left inverse.</fn>
            </investigation>
        </subsection>
        <conclusion>
            <title>Concluding Remarks</title>
            <p>
                Using row reduction to get inverses is the standard introductory way to find them.  It does take patience and precision, both of which can be bad at.  Computers can do this very well though.  Use the code below to help you check your work while practicing.  You should also learn to use the computer to help you check your other calculations.  (Make use of the <url href="quickref-linalg.pdf">Linear Algebra Quick Reference</url> and you can use the box below or go to the <url href="https://sagecell.sagemath.org/" >SageMathCell</url> main page.)
            </p>
            <sage>
                <input>
                    <xi:include href="sage_code/matrix_inverses.sage" parse="text"/>
                </input>
                <output></output>
            </sage>
        </conclusion>
    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Linear Maps and Matrices</title>
        <subsection>
            <title>Matrices as Maps</title>
            <investigation>
                <p>
                    Let
                    <me>
                        A=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                1 \amp 0 \\
                                -3 \amp 1
                            \end{array}
                        \right),\ 
                        \vec{w}=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                5\\
                                1
                            \end{array}
                        \right),\ \mbox{ and }
                        \vec{v}=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rr}
                                -1\\
                                10
                            \end{array}
                        \right).\ 
                    </me>
                    We can "quickly" verify that <m>A(2\vec{v}+\vec{w})=2(A\vec{v})+A\vec{w}</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \\
                                    -3 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \left(
                                2\left(
                                    \begin{array}{rr}
                                        -1\\
                                        10
                                    \end{array}
                                \right)+
                                \left(
                                    \begin{array}{rr}
                                        5\\
                                        1
                                    \end{array}
                                \right)
                            \right)\amp=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \\
                                    -3 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    -2+5\\
                                    20+1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1(-2+5)+0(20+1)\\
                                    -3(-2+5)+1(20+1)\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1(-2)+0(20)\\
                                    -3(-2)+1(20)\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)+
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1(5)+0(1)\\
                                    -3(5)+1(1)\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp=
                            2\left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1(-1)+0(10)\\
                                    -3(-1)+1(10)\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)+
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \\
                                    -3 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    5\\
                                    1\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp=
                            2\left(
                                \left(
                                    \begin{array}{rr}
                                        1 \amp 0 \\
                                        -3 \amp 1
                                    \end{array}
                                \right)
                                \left(
                                    \begin{array}{rr}
                                        -1\\
                                        10\\
                                    \end{array}
                                \right)
                            \right)+
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp 0 \\
                                    -3 \amp 1
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    5\\
                                    1\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    What is true, though perhaps not immediately obvious, is that this doesn't depend on the values of <m>A</m>, <m>\vec{w}</m>, or <m>\vec{v}</m>.
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <theorem xml:id="matrix_transformation">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        If <m>A</m> is an <m>n\times m</m> matrix, <m>\vec{v},\vec{w}\in\mathbb{R}^m</m>, and <m>a,b\in\mathbb{R}</m>, then
                        <me>A(a\vec{v}+b\vec{w})=a\, A\vec{v}+b\, A\vec{w},</me>
                        that is, multiplication by a matrix is a linear transformation.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </theorem>
            <investigation>
                <p>
                    The previous relationship works both ways.  Define <m>T:\mathbb{R}^3\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^2</m> by
                    <me>T(\left\lt x_1,x_2,x_3\right\gt)=\left\lt x_1-2x_2, 2x_2-3x_3\right\gt.</me>
                    If we apply this to each element of the elementary basis <m>\mathcal{E}_3</m> for <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> we get:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            T(\left\lt 1,0,0\right\gt)\amp=\left\lt 1, 0\right\gt,
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            T(\left\lt 0,1,0\right\gt)\amp=\left\lt -2, 2\right\gt,\ \mbox{ and }
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            T(\left\lt 0,0,1\right\gt)\amp=\left\lt 0, -3\right\gt.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    But, this is the same as multiplying each of the vectors by the matrix
                    <me>
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{rrr}
                                1 \amp -2 \amp 0\\
                                0 \amp 2 \amp -3
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    in which each column is the image of one of the elementary vectors.
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <theorem xml:id="transformation_matrix">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        If <m>T</m> is a linear transformation from <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, then it may be represented as multiplication by
                        <me>
                            A=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{cccc}
                                    T(\vec{e}_1) \amp T(\vec{e}_2) \amp \cdots \amp T(\vec{e}_m)\\
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </me>
                        in which each column is the image of one of the elementary basis vectors for <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </theorem>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Row, Column, and Null Spaces (again)</title>
            <p>
                The row, column, and null spaces for the matrix
                <me>
                    A=\left[
                        \begin{array}{rrr}
                            1 \amp 0 \amp -1\\
                            0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                            0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
                        \end{array}
                    \right]
                </me>
                are
                <md>
                    <mrow>Row\ A\amp=\left\{\left\lt 1,0,-1\right\gt, \left\lt 0,1,0\right\gt \right\}, </mrow>
                    <mrow>Col\ A\amp=\left\{\left\lt 1,0,0\right\gt, \left\lt 0,1,1\right\gt \right\}, and</mrow>
                    <mrow>Nul\ A\amp=\left\{\left\lt 1,0,1\right\gt\right\}.</mrow>
                </md>
                We can see these visually in <xref ref="row_null_to_col_zero"/> where you can see the plain of the row space transition to the plain of the column space while the vector of the null space transitions to zero.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="row_null_to_col_zero">
                <caption>Row and Null Spaces Transitioning to Column Space and Zero</caption>
                <image width="50%" source="images/row_col_null.gif"/>
            </figure>
            <p>
                If we multiply each of the standard basis elements by the matrix <m>A</m> we get
                <md>
                    <mrow> \vec{e}_1=\left\lt 1,0,0 \right\gt \leadsto \left\lt 1,0,0 \right\gt</mrow>
                    <mrow> \vec{e}_2=\left\lt 0,1,0 \right\gt \leadsto \left\lt 0,1,1 \right\gt</mrow>
                    <mrow> \vec{e}_3=\left\lt 0,0,1 \right\gt \leadsto \left\lt -1,0,0 \right\gt</mrow>
                </md>
                which are the columns of the matrix.  The domain of the transformation defined by <m>A</m> is therefore <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, <xref ref="pre_image_A"/>. Meanwhile, the image (or range) of the transformation is the column space of <m>A</m> which is a copy of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>, <xref ref="image_A"/>.  So the basis for <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> has been turned into a basis for a plain that is a copy of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.<fn>This is the perspective that we will spend time on in <xref ref="section_coordinates"/>.</fn>
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
                <figure xml:id="pre_image_A">
                    <caption>Standard Basis Before Transformation</caption>
                    <image width="50%" source="images/pre_image_A.png"/>
                </figure>
                <figure xml:id="image_A">
                    <caption>Basis After Transformation by <m>A</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%" source="images/image_A.png"/>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>
                We can also define a linear transformation <m>T_A</m> algebraically by
                <me>
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{c}
                            x\\ y \\ z
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                    \stackrel{T_A}{\leadsto}
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{c}
                            x-z\\ y \\ y
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                </me>
                which has the same effect as multiplying the vector <m>\left\lt x,y,z\right\gt</m> by <m>A</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                We have three ways to think of each transformation.  Each transformation is a manipulation of a physical space, a change from one basis to another, or a series of algebraic instructions.  All of these are reasonable ways to view a transformation and which perspective we use depends on what we wish to accomplish.
            </p>
        </subsection>
    </section>

<!-- Change of Bases -->

    <section xml:id="section_coordinates">
        <title>Change of Bases/Coordinates</title>
        <subsection>
            <title>Coordinate Systems</title>
            <p>
                Suppose that we want to walk to the point <m>(2,3)</m> from the origin, how might we get there?
            </p>
            <sidebyside widths="30% 37%">
                <stack>
                    <p>
                        We can get from the origin to the point <m>(2,3)</m> by walking east 2 blocks and north 3.
                        <me>
                            2\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 0 \end{array}\right)
                            +3\left(\begin{array}{r}0 \\ 1 \end{array}\right)
                            =\left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 3 \end{array}\right)
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </stack>
                <figure xml:id="basis_e">
                    <caption>Path one with the elementary basis <m>\mathcal{E}_2</m>.</caption>
                    <image source="images/basis_e.png"/>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            <sidebyside widths="30% 40%">
                <stack>
                    <p>
                        We can get there by walking northeast(ish) 3 blocks and northwest(ish) 1.
                        <me>
                            3\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 1/2 \end{array}\right)
                            +\left(\begin{array}{r}-1 \\ 3/2 \end{array}\right)
                            =\left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 3 \end{array}\right)
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </stack>
                <figure xml:id="basis_b">
                    <caption>Path two with some basis <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.</caption>
                    <image source="images/basis_b.png"/>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            <sidebyside widths="30% 48%">
                <stack>
                    <p>
                        We can get there by walking northwest(ish) 2 blocks and northeast(ish) 4.
                        <me>
                            2\left(\begin{array}{r}-1 \\ 1 \end{array}\right)
                            +4\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 1/4 \end{array}\right)
                            =\left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 3 \end{array}\right)
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </stack>
                <figure xml:id="basis_d">
                    <caption>Path three with some basis <m>\mathcal{D}</m>.</caption>
                    <image source="images/basis_d.png"/>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>
                In each case you get to the same place but using different paths.  That is because in each case we are using different bases or coordinate systems.
            </p>
            <p>
                In <xref ref="basis_e"/> we follow the vectors in the basis
                <me>
                    \mathcal{E}_2=
                    \left\{
                        \vec{e}_1=\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 0 \end{array}\right),
                        \vec{e}_2=\left(\begin{array}{r}0 \\ 1 \end{array}\right)
                    \right\}.
                </me>
                We say that the <m>\mathcal{E}_2</m>-coordinates for <m>(2,3)</m> are
                <me>
                    Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2}
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                </me>
                because
                <me>
                    2\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 0 \end{array}\right)
                    +3\left(\begin{array}{r}0 \\ 1 \end{array}\right)
                    =\left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 3 \end{array}\right).
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                In <xref ref="basis_b"/> we follow the vectors in the basis
                <me>
                    \mathcal{B}=
                    \left\{
                        \vec{\beta}_1=\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 1/2 \end{array}\right),
                        \vec{\beta}_2=\left(\begin{array}{r}-1 \\ 3/2 \end{array}\right)
                    \right\}.
                </me>
                We say that the <m>\mathcal{B}</m>-coordinates for <m>(2,3)</m> are
                <me>
                    Rep_{\mathcal{B}}
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            3 \\ 1
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                </me>
                because
                <me>
                    3\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 1/2 \end{array}\right)
                    +1\left(\begin{array}{r}-1 \\ 3/2 \end{array}\right)
                    =\left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 3 \end{array}\right).
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                In <xref ref="basis_d"/> we follow the vectors in the basis
                <me>
                    \mathcal{D}=
                    \left\{
                        \vec{\delta}_1=\left(\begin{array}{r}-1 \\ 1 \end{array}\right),
                        \vec{\delta}_2=\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 1/4 \end{array}\right)
                    \right\}.
                </me>
                We say that the <m>\mathcal{D}</m>-coordinates for <m>(2,3)</m> are
                <me>
                    Rep_{\mathcal{D}}
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 4
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                </me>
                because
                <me>
                    2\left(\begin{array}{r}-1 \\ 1 \end{array}\right)
                    +4\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 1/4 \end{array}\right)
                    =\left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 3 \end{array}\right).
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                In each case the coordinates for the point <m>(2,3)</m> are the coefficients for a linear combination of basis vectors.
            </p>
            <definition>
                <title><m>\mathcal{B}</m>-Coordinates</title>
                <idx><h>coordinate system</h></idx>
                <idx><h><m>\mathcal{B}</m>-coordinates</h></idx>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Given a basis <me>\mathcal{B}=\left\{\vec{\beta}_1,\, \vec{\beta}_2,\, \ldots,\, \vec{\beta}_k\right\}</me> the <term><m>\mathcal{B}</m>-coordinates</term> for a point or vector <m>\vec{p}</m> are the coefficients <m>b_1,\, b_2,\, \ldots,\, b_k</m> so that <me>\vec{p}=b_1\vec{\beta}_1+b_2\vec{\beta}_2+\cdots+b_k\vec{\beta}_k</me> and we write
                        <me>
                            Rep_{\mathcal{B}}(\vec{p})=
                            \left[
                                \begin{array}{l}
                                    b_1\\ b_2\\ \vdots\\ b_k
                                \end{array}
                            \right].
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>
            <p>
                Finally, we can connect this to matrices by observing that if the columns of a matrix are the basis vectors then when we multiply that by a representation we get our point, for example
                <me>
                    \left(\vec{\beta}_1\ \vec{\beta}_2\right)Rep_{\mathcal{B}}
                    \left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 3 \end{array}\right)
                    =
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{rr}
                            1 \amp -1\\
                            1/2 \amp 3/2
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                    \left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 1 \end{array}\right)
                    =
                    \left(\begin{array}{r}2 \\ 3 \end{array}\right).                   
                </me>
            </p>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Changing Bases</title>
            <investigation>
                <title><m>\mathcal{B}</m> to <m>\mathcal{E}_2</m></title>
                <p>
                    The elementary or standard basis is
                    <me>
                        \mathcal{E}_2=
                        \left\{
                            \vec{e}_1=\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 0 \end{array}\right),
                            \vec{e}_2=\left(\begin{array}{r}0 \\ 1 \end{array}\right)
                        \right\}.
                    </me>
                    Let <m>\mathcal{B}</m> be the basis
                    <me>
                        \mathcal{B}=
                        \left\{
                            \vec{\beta}_1=\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 1/2 \end{array}\right),
                            \vec{\beta}_2=\left(\begin{array}{r}-1 \\ 3/2 \end{array}\right)
                        \right\}
                    </me>
                    as above.  If we have a vector written in terms of <m>\mathcal{B}</m>,
                    <me>
                        Rep_{\mathcal{B}}\left(\vec{v}\right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                -1 \\ 3
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    and we want <m>Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2}(\vec{v})</m> then we multiply by the matrix
                    <me>
                        Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{E}_2}=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp -1 \\ 
                                    1/2\amp 3/2 
                                \end{array}
                            \right).
                    </me>
                    So we get,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2}(\vec{v})\amp = Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{E}_2}\, Rep_{\mathcal{B}}\left(\vec{v}\right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = 
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp -1 \\ 
                                    1/2\amp 3/2 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)\,
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{r}
                                    -1 \\ 3
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{r}
                                    -4 \\ 4
                                \end{array}
                            \right).
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    To change from any basis <me>\mathcal{B}=\left\{\vec{\beta}_1,\, \vec{\beta}_2,\, \ldots,\, \vec{\beta}_k\right\}</me> to <m>\mathcal{E}_k</m> multiply by the matrix
                    <me>Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{E}_k}=\left(\vec{\beta}_1\ \vec{\beta}_2\ \cdots\ \vec{\beta}_k\right)</me>
                    each of whose columns is an element of <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title><m>\mathcal{E}_2</m> to <m>\mathcal{B}</m></title>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\mathcal{E}_2</m> and <m>\mathcal{B}</m> be the same as before and suppose
                    <me>
                        Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2}(\vec{w})=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                7\\-2
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    to change from <m>\mathcal{E}_2</m> to <m>\mathcal{B}</m> multiply by the matrix
                    <me>
                        Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2,\mathcal{B}}=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp -1 \\ 
                                    1/2\amp 3/2 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)^{-1}=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    3/4 \amp 1/2 \\ 
                                    -1/4\amp 1/2 
                                \end{array}
                            \right).
                    </me>
                    So we get,
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            Rep_{\mathcal{B}}(\vec{w})\amp = Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2,\mathcal{B}}\, Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2}\left(\vec{w}\right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = 
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    3/4 \amp 1/2 \\ 
                                    -1/4\amp 1/2 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)\,
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{r}
                                    7 \\ -2
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp =
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{r}
                                    17/4 \\ -11/4
                                \end{array}
                            \right).
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    To change from <m>\mathcal{E}_k</m> to any basis <me>\mathcal{B}=\left\{\vec{\beta}_1,\, \vec{\beta}_2,\, \ldots,\, \vec{\beta}_k\right\}</me>  multiply by the matrix
                    <me>Rep_{\mathcal{E}_k,\mathcal{B}}=(Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{E}_k})^{-1}=\left(\vec{\beta}_1\ \vec{\beta}_2\ \cdots\ \vec{\beta}_k\right)^{-1}.</me>
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title><m>\mathcal{B}</m> to <m>\mathcal{D}</m></title>
                <p>
                    Finally, let
                   <me>
                        \mathcal{D}=
                        \left\{
                            \vec{\delta}_1=\left(\begin{array}{r}-1 \\ 1 \end{array}\right),
                            \vec{\delta}_2=\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ 1/4 \end{array}\right)
                        \right\}.
                    </me>
                    and let <m>\mathcal{B}</m> and <m>\mathcal{E}_2</m> be as before.  Suppose also that
                   <me>
                        Rep_{\mathcal{B}}\left(\vec{v}\right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                -1 \\ 3
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    if we want to find <m>Rep_{\mathcal{D}}(\vec{v})</m> then multiply by the matrix
                    <md>
                        <mrow>Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{D}}\amp=Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2,\mathcal{D}}Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{E}_2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    -1 \amp 1 \\ 
                                    1\amp 1/4 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)^{-1}
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp -1 \\ 
                                    1/2\amp 3/2 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    -1/5 \amp 4/5 \\ 
                                    4/5\amp 4/5 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1 \amp -1 \\ 
                                    1/2\amp 3/2 
                                \end{array}
                            \right)
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=
                            \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1/5 \amp 7/5 \\ 
                                    6/5\amp 2/5 
                                \end{array}
                            \right).
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                    So that we get
                    <me>
                        Rep_{\mathcal{D}}(\vec{v})=Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{D}}Rep_{\mathcal{B}}(\vec{v})=
                        \left(
                                \begin{array}{rr}
                                    1/5 \amp 7/5 \\ 
                                    6/5\amp 2/5 
                                \end{array}
                        \right)
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                -1 \\ 3
                            \end{array}
                        \right)=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                4 \\ 0
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    We can verify that this is correct because
                    <me>
                        -1\vec{\beta}_1+3\vec{\beta}_2=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                -4 \\ 4
                            \end{array}
                        \right)
                    </me>
                    and
                    <me>
                        4\vec{\delta}_1+0\vec{\delta}_2=
                        \left(
                            \begin{array}{r}
                                -4 \\ 4
                            \end{array}
                        \right).
                    </me>
                    In general if
                    <me>\mathcal{B}=\left\{\vec{\beta}_1,\, \vec{\beta}_2,\, \ldots,\, \vec{\beta}_k\right\}</me>
                    and
                    <me>\mathcal{D}=\left\{\vec{\delta}_1,\, \vec{\delta}_2,\, \ldots,\, \vec{\delta}_k\right\}</me>
                    then
                    <md>
                        <mrow>Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{D}}\amp=Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2,\mathcal{D}}Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{E}_2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=(Rep_{\mathcal{D},\mathcal{E}_2})^{-1}Rep_{\mathcal{B},\mathcal{E}_2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp=\left(\vec{\delta}_1\ \vec{\delta}_2\ \cdots\ \vec{\delta}_k\right)^{-1}
                            \left(\vec{\beta}_1\ \vec{\beta}_2\ \cdots\ \vec{\beta}_k\right).
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </investigation>
            <investigation>
                <title>Back to the Beginning</title>
                <p>
                    We started above with
                <me>
                    Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2}
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right),\ 
                    Rep_{\mathcal{B}}
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            3 \\ 1
                        \end{array}
                    \right),\ \mbox{ and }
                    Rep_{\mathcal{D}}
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 4
                        \end{array}
                    \right).                    
                </me>
                Now, we know that if we multiply the first one,
                <me>
                    Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2}\left(\begin{array}{r}2\\3\end{array}\right)=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{r}
                            2 \\ 3
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                </me>
                by
                <me>
                    Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2,\mathcal{B}}=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{rr}
                            3/4 \amp 1/2 \\ 
                            -1/4\amp 1/2 
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                </me>
                or
                <me>
                    Rep_{\mathcal{E}_2,\mathcal{D}}=
                    \left(
                        \begin{array}{rr}
                            -1/5 \amp 4/5 \\ 
                            4/5\amp 4/5 
                        \end{array}
                    \right)
                </me>
                we get the other two.  That is we have a reliable, algorithmic way to change from one basis to another in the same dimension.
                </p>
            </investigation>
        </subsection>
        <subsection>
            <title>Changing Morphisms</title>
            <investigation>
                <title>Change a transformation of <m>\mathcal{E}_2</m> to one from <m>\mathcal{B}</m> to <m>\mathcal{D}</m></title>
